04466nam a22006735i 9780813542577DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20042004nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135425777 a10.36019/97808135425772doi  a(DE-B1597)530349  a(OCoLC)508263110  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPN1995.9.H6bH667 2004 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.43/616422204aThe Horror Film /cStephen Prince. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2004] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRutgers Depth of Field Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Dark Genre and Its Paradoxes -- tShadow-Souls and Strange Adventures: Horror and the Supernatural in European Silent Film -- tBefore Sound: Universal, Silent Cinema, and the Last of the Horror-Spectaculars -- tChildren of the Night -- tThe Horrors of War -- tPostmodern Elements of the Contemporary Horror Film -- tDread, Taboo, and The Thing: Toward a Social Theory of the Horror Film -- tToward an Aesthetics of Cinematic Horror -- tScraping Bottom: Splatter and the Herschell Gordon Lewis Oeuvre -- tMondo Horror: Carnivalizing the Taboo -- tHorror and Art-Dread -- tHorror and the Holocaust: Genre Elements in Schindler's List and Psycho -- tDevelopmental Differences in Responses to Horror -- tThe Appeal of Horror and Suspense -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this volume, Stephen Prince has collected essays reviewing the history of the horror film and the psychological reasons for its persistent appeal, as well as discussions of the developmental responses of young adult viewers and children to the genre. The book focuses on recent postmodern examples such as The Blair Witch Project. In a daring move, the volume also examines Holocaust films in relation to horror. Part One features essays on the silent and classical Hollywood eras. Part Two covers the postWorld War II era and discusses the historical, aesthetic, and psychological characteristics of contemporary horror films. In contrast to horror during the classical Hollywood period, contemporary horror features more graphic and prolonged visualizations of disturbing and horrific imagery, as well as other distinguishing characteristics. Princes introduction provides an overview of the genre, contextualizing the readings that follow. Stephen Prince is professor of communications at Virginia Tech. He has written many film books, including Classical Film Violence: Designing and Regulating Brutality in Hollywood Cinema, 19301968, and has edited Screening Violence, also in the Depth of Field Series.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aHorror filmsxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aPrince, Stephen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813542577423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813542577.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK